Wash and dry all produce. Bring a large #pot{} of salted water to a boil. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Halve, peel, and thinly slice @shallot{1}. Finely chop @parsley{¼%oz}. Once water is boiling, add @linguine{6%oz} to pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve 1 cup pasta cooking water, then drain.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{1%tsp} in a large pan over medium heat. Add shallot and cook until softened, ~{3-5%minutes}, tossing. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Add @seitan crumbles{8%oz} and @Tuscan heat spice{1%tbsp}(to taste—it's spicy) to pan, breaking up seitan into pieces with a #spatula{} or #wooden spoon{}. Cook until lightly browned and crisped, ~{3-5%minutes}, stirring occasionally. Stir in garlic and most of the parsley and cook until fragrant, another ~{1%minute} (save a few big pinches of parsley for garnish).

Stir @diced tomatoes{1%can}, @veggie stock concentrate{1}, and 1 cup water into pan. Bring to a boil, then lower heat and let simmer until slightly reduced, ~{5-10%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

> TIP: Give the Bolognese a taste. If it seems sharp, try adding up to 1 tsp sugar to mellow it out.

Add linguine, half the @Parmesan cheese{¼%cup}, and a splash of pasta cooking water to pan and toss to thoroughly combine.

> TIP: If Bolognese seems dry, add more pasta cooking water until it's nice and saucy.

Divide pasta between plates. Garnish with reserved parsley and remaining Parmesan.